@misc{boyd_2016,
   author = {Boyd, Danah},
   title = {RE: the "ecosystem of prediction"},
   month = {2016-03-16},
   abstract = {Hi Tim!  TBH, I wasn’t trying to use ecosystem as a metaphor.  I was using it more in the everyday vernacular where it’s about a large network of interconnected practices.  I respect your post and critique of the information ecosystem but as someone who was never trained in environmental thinking, it literally didn’t dawn on me that environmental thinkers would be critical of this popular usage.

danah

> On Mar 16, 2016, at 3:51 PM, Norris, Timothy <tnorris@miami.edu> wrote:
>
> Dear Danah,
>
> I hope this find you well! I have a quick question. If you have a moment, that would be great, if not, no worries.
>
> In your 2015 Parker Lecture “What World are We Building” you refer to an “ecosystem of prediction.” I am very curious as to how this metaphor works for you. I would love to hear your thoughts on how you use this metaphor, what meaning you give to it, and how it performs work for your argument.
>
> Some context: I have a social justice background that has now been heavily influenced by environmental thinking (I am a Human Geographer with a focus on social justice, extractive industries and conservation). I am becoming extremely critical of the “Information Ecosystem” metaphor of which the use started several decades ago. Indeed I have written a blog and am working on a more lengthy critical engagement with this metaphor (forthcoming). Your answer would inform my thinking even more on this subject (part of my research). As an aside, at the 2015 DLF I asked Safyia U. Noble the same question (after her keynote) and had a good discussion with her. It seems that perhaps the social justice and environmental conversations have something to share in the world of data, information, and what the internet is to become.
>
> Kind regards
>
> Tim},
